    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-12-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-05-25T21:00:00-05:00" n="301" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d301">
                <head>No. 301<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>On August 22, 1952, Under Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_BRUCEDKE1"
                        >Bruce</persName> sent a personal telegram to Ambassadors <persName
                        corresp="#p_GIFFORDWS1">Gifford</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_DUNNJC1"
                        >Dunn</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_DRAPERWHJ1">Draper</persName>,
                        <persName corresp="#p_BUNKERE1">Bunker</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_KENNANGF1">Kennan</persName>, and <persName
                        corresp="#p_DONNELLYWJ1">Donnelly</persName>, informing them of his desire
                    to hold a meeting in London at which the present situation in Europe would be
                    examined in order to make recommendations to the Secretary of State for further
                    steps which the United States might take to strengthen its position. <persName
                        corresp="#p_BRUCEDKE1">Bruce</persName> stated his intention of keeping the
                    number of participants small and outlined a tentative agenda. (Telegram 1267 to
                    London, August 22, repeated to Paris, Rome, Moscow, and Bonn; 120.4341/8–2252)
                    Concerning the agenda and the background papers prepared for the meetings, see
                    the briefing memorandum, September 18, <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>.</p>
            </div>
